ownPages.content:
A class which configures logger to print a log message to the console.PrintLogger

setGlobalJacquardSDKLogger Sets the global Logger instance used by all code in Jacquard SDK.

You do not need to set this - the default logger prints log messages to the console using Log#println(int, String, String) , ignoring LogLevel LogLevel . You can also set a default logger with log level which you desire, or you may implement your own custom Logger type. initialize Initializes a default logger Logger with a log level which you desire.

You can also use PrintLogger with a default log levels. initialize Initializes a default logger with a log level LogLevel , LogLevel , LogLevel , LogLevel .

ownPages.title: Signal
ownPages.content:
A naive reimplementation of rxjava's Observable<T>

Produces an observable stream of T. All operations are single-threaded, but should otherwise be thread-safe.create Signal factory method create signal factory method empty empty signal factory empty errored signal factory from create Signal[T] from Iterable[T] from create Signal[T] from a T just create Signal[T] from a T (alias to allow Collections) merge combine multiple signals of the same type into one merge merge a list of signals of the same type into one hasObservers error error out this signal next provide a new value to this signal hasError isComplete complete mark this signal as being completed map transform Signal[T] to Signal[U] using T -> U flatMap transform Signal[T] to Signal[U] using T -> Signal[U] switchMap transform Signal[T] to Signal[U] using T -> Signal[U] and complete previous inner observable before emitting. filter remove elements from this Signal that do not match the predicate takeWhile retrieve the beginning of this signal while the predicate is true take retrieve the first count items from this signal first retrieve the first element of this signal drop ignore the first count items from this signal dropWhile ignore the first items of this signal while the predicate holds distinct distinctUntilChanged sticky last retrieve the last item of this signal scan collate this signal into an accumulator shared share any previous operations across subsequent observers timeout timeout this signal after timeoms milliseconds timeout timeout this signal after timeoms milliseconds recoverWith Recovers this Signal if it encounters an error by returning a new Signal.

The exception can be inspected to either return a new signal, or another error if it should not be handled. delay delay all outputs from this signal by

delayms countDownTimer Schedule a countdown until a time in the future, with regular notifications on intervals along the way. tapError Forwards errors to the designated callback without causing subscribe side-effects forward Forwards all events from this Signal to the target signal tap Forwards all next values to the specified consumer for a side-effecting operation. tapCompletion Forwards completion to the specified consumer for a side-effecting operation. observeOn Executes downstream operators on the provided Executor . onNext onComplete onError onTerminate Subscribes to onError and onComplete of this signal.

consumer will be called with a null Throwable if this has completed successfully, if there is an error, it will be non-null. observe Observes this signal using the specified onNext and onTerminate. observe observe events on this signal, unsubscribe the Subscription to stop observing consume convenience method to observe all values on this Signal and ignore them, causes side-effects to run.

ownPages.title: CommandResponseStatus
ownPages.content:
Map status codes to errorsOK

ERROR_UNSUPPORTED The domain or opcode is unsupported. ERROR_BAD_PARAM The parameters to this command were incorrect/invalid. ERROR_BATTERY The device has a critically low battery and will not execute the command. ERROR_HARDWARE We have experienced a failure in some hardware component. ERROR_AUTH The key in an authentication call was incorrect, or there has been no authentication yet and this call must happen on an authenticated connection. ERROR_DEVICE_TYPE_INFO The device has an invalid device type. ERROR_INVALID_STATE Invalid state to perform requested operation. ERROR_FLASH_ACCESS Error accessing Flash for either read/write or erase operation request. ERROR_CHECKSUM Checksum error. ERROR_BUSY Error Busy - e.g. Busy updating Interposer FW. ERROR_APP_TIMEOUT Error Generated in APP only ERROR_APP_UNKNOWN Error Generated in APP only ERROR_UNKNOWN Some internal, unknown error has occurred. values

The different states on the connection process.ConnectionState

preparingToConnect This is initial state, and also the state while waiting for reconnection. connecting Connecting with approximate progress. initializing Initializing with approximate progress. The progress continues on from the progress reported by the connecting state. configuring Configuring with approximate progress. The progress continues on from the progress reported by the initializing state. connected returns the connected tag ready to use. Note this is not a terminal state - the stream may ho back to disconnected, and then subsequently reconnect again. disconnected This terminal state will only be reached if reconnecting or retrying is not possible. ofPreparingToConnect

ownPages.title: TagConnectionStateMachine
ownPages.content:
A state machine for handling connecting to a tag. It receives events from BleAdapter via TagConnectionStateMachine . State changes can be observed via TagConnectionStateMachine .

TagConnectionStateMachine has two child state machines. First events from onConnectStateEvent are forwarded to a TagPairingStateMachine . Once the tag is paired the child will be replaced with a ProtocolInitializationStateMachine . TagConnectionStateMachine will emit ConnectionState . When the connection has been established the ConnectionState will be emitted with an instance of the connected tag.TagConnectionStateMachine Creates a new instance of TagConnectionStateMachine. getState onStateEvent connect Starts the connection process. destroy

ownPages.title: README
ownPages.content:
Getting started

Jacquard by Google weaves new digital experiences into the things you love, wear, and use every day to give you the power to do more and be more. Jacquard SDK is a way to connect Jacquard interactions within your apps. Create an app and bring it to life with swipes and taps through the Jacquard SDK.

What do I need to get started?

The Android Jacquard SDK supports Android versions 23 and greater.

You will need the Jacquard Tag with a supported Jacquard product (all come with one tag). Currently supported products are:

  • Levi's Trucker Jacket
  • Samsonite Konnect-i backpack
  • Saint Laurent Cit-e Backpack You can find links to purchase these products on the Google Jacquard website.

If you have just opened a new retail Jacquard product, your tag probably needs a firmware update (and perhaps charging). Review the steps in the Updating Firmware page.

Sample App

To run the example project, clone the repo, and run the Android project from the sample directory first. For more detailed instructions, see the full documentation.

Next Steps

The best way to get started with the Jacquard SDK is to follow our tutorial.

Once you have completed the tutorial, the best place to go next is the API Overview which will explain the features of your Jacquard tag and gear, and how to use the API. After that, check out the API Documentation (available in the table of contents on the left of every page) and build your awesome app :)
